<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-250-004  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 250 004.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  March 16 1990 n1386* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services (England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM &quot;planning a Systems Management Architecture.&quot; (plan tointegrate incompatible utility programs under a single softwareframework)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (product development).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     Utility ProgramsSelf-Organizing SystemsProduct DevelopmentSystems SoftwareSoftware ArchitectureCompatible Software.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>IBM &quot;PLANNING A SYSTEMS MANAGEMENT ARCHITECTURE&quot;andM;In an effort to muscle its way further into the market for facilitiesmanagement, IBM is working on an architecture to automate data centreoperations.andP;  According to Computer System News this scheme is knowninformally within IBM as Systems Management Architecture, SMA, and isexpected to integrate hundreds of incompatible utility programs under asingle software framework.andP;  With such an architecture in place IBM would bein a position to squeeze third party software houses out of the market.andP;  Theoverall aim of Systems Management Architecture is to enable computer systemsto manage themselves with minimal user intervention.andP;  To fulfil this aim IBMis reported to be enhancing its not over-highly-regarded NetView networkmanagement tools so that they can carry out system management functions.andO;However, the company may well have a fight on its hands to get third partieswith strong rival systems management products to toe the Systems ManagementArchitecture line in a market that is relatively new to IBM - but it canalways win companies' allegiance by bankrolling development in return forminority equity stakes in them.andO;</TEXT></DOC>